It also has some magnificent view for the sunset and free parking all day from 7AM to 7PM.
It has restrooms, cold water dispenser and wheelchair accessible parking.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Finally, I came there. This place is an deep dream that I want to visit, so I am very grateful to be able to set foot there.

Free of charge to sight seeing and walking around, please you can more explore about bird watching.

One of building, on the information area, they made the design interior very nice, informative and make you know a lot about wetlands including ecosistem.

If you are explorer and need more product knowlegde, high recommended to visit!

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Awesome place away from the city!!! We went in the evening in July. Mosquitoes did not bother us at all. We saw bats, crocodiles (usually by the bridge to the loop trail), and of course, mud skippers. We did not see any water monitors (huge lizards). They must not be out in evening?

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Excellent place for a walk and to see some wildlife up close. Please don‚Äôt litter if you go here, too many people have and it spoils what is otherwise a fantastic place showing how biodiversity and cities can exist closely.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: A nature fun environment with migrant birds. One could easily spend at least 2 to 3 hours enjoying the natural surrounding especially during low tide. I saw 3 crocodiles, (one of which has a missing tail piece) resting on the wetland.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Best Place to spend a day walking and enjoying nature. Lots to see. Bring water and insect repellent.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: The wild side of Singapore was peaceful and lovely to walk around. Was able to see a huge saltwater crocodile, monitor lizard and various birds. A refreshing change from the manicured parks and far from the craziness of the city centre

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: We had a lovely walk in Sungei Buloh wetland reserve. Even managed to spot a hornbill while walking the trail. Loved the serenity, bird calls and cools Breeze almost the trees. if you need an escape from our concrete jungle head to Sungei Buloh for an escape into nature. Go before 7pm as it closes.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Quiet and chilly nature reserve, very ‚Äúwalk-able‚Äù from end to end with short and well maintained trails / walkways.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: It is an okay place. There is a quite diverse selection of wildlife, but is very crowded. It does have decent views but is full of school children. The walks are quite nice and it is fairly enjoyable by yourself.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Things has changed so much since my last visit 15yrs back.

Board bus service 925 from Kranji mrt to the carpark just outside Sungei buloh. Its a short 10mins walk to the visitor centre.

There is No entrance fee!

Place is well maintained with toilets, rest points, paved path etc. Definitely should come for a visit to check out the nature in our concrete jungle. Ideal for nature lovers, couples, kids to spend a good half day.

There are crocs and we spotted 2 during our trek but they couldnt be bothered with us. Check out the photos!

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Simply one of the best places in singapore for just casual walking while admiring the scenic beauty of nature and a vast variety of animals. Would recommend 10/10, the thrill of finding these wild animals beats the Zoo for sure. Heres some photos i took at sungei buloh

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Sungei Buloh Wetlands Reserve is one of the fascinating nature walk in Singapore.

An escape from the concrete jungle, you can indulge in greenery and scenery. Take your time off and come with your cameras.

Do prepare a bottle of water and some repellent. And if you are lucky, you may see crocodiles lurking near the banks (not the savings bank if you know what I mean)

Area still under construction to improve our experience but the whole place is the best we can get to nature on mainland singapore.

Totally thrilled about walking around this reserve and loving it as it does takes your mind off the hectic urban lifestyle.

Furthermore it's free..but having your own transport would be a big bonus. Nonetheless there are shuttle buses catered so, not an excuse not to go and visit =)

Rmb, water bottle, repellent, umbrella(in case it rains) and wear covered shoes for ease of walking

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Very nice place for a walk with family.. Everything is good except two things msquitoes and road condition.  Long pants with mosquito patch or spray is must for kids. Wild mosquitoes are really aggressive..

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Always love to visit Sungei Buloh, one of the few places one can come close to nature in Singapore. You may be able to catch a glimpse of crocodile or some exotic birds if you are lucky !

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: So beautiful! Finally some real nature in Singapore. Lots of mossies though but also a huge amount of fish and even crocodiles! Not to mention the birdlife here. You can even see Malaysia on the other side of the water. I recommend spending at least 2h here and not too late in the day. Best time, I guess, is very early or before sunset when the wildlife is active the most.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: If you wanna go close to nature, this is nature at its best in SG. We were to lucky to spot a lazy monitor lizard & 2 aligators! There were also crabs & lotsa mudskippers... love this place!

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
This is my first visit to this place. I never think that Singapore still has a very beautiful mangrove forest. If you are a nature lover, you are bound to come to this place because this place is really fresh and if you are lucky, you will find wild animals such as squirrels, beavers, lizards, crabs, fishes, crocodiles and more.
The ideal time to visit is morning and when the tide is low. Do not forget to bring binoculars, cameras if you come here. For those who are allergic to mosquito bites you are required to carry anti-mosquito lotion. Overall, it takes 2 to 3 hours to explore. Do not worry, this place has a flat road and this place is safe to visit.
To get to Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve by bus, board SMRT Bus 925 from Kranji MRT Station. Alight at Kranji Reservoir Carpark B to Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve Extension‚Äôs Visitor Centre.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Great scenic views and the chance to spot abundant wildlife makes this an excellent choice to visit. Trails aren't exceedingly difficult, most are well-paced with enough leg room for a small group of people to walk together. I have spotted storks, huge pelicans, all types of herons, monitor lizards in the pond, monitor lizards on the trails, a shocking amount of spiders, huge mudskippers that are surprisingly adorable to watch, and numerous other encounters etc. Recommended for a respite away from the urban landscape, the only drawback being the hard to reach location. Going by public transport requires one to change several buses and walk for a short while, not that hard by any means but more arduous than normal. I enjoy photography on the weekends there and it remains one of my favourite outdoor spots in Singapore. *photos have been edited

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: there is just so much wildlife here in Sungei Buloh it's hard to believe it exists in the bustling city of Singapore. It has estuarian crocodiles, large tree snakes, common malayan water monitor lizards, common sandpiper, Chinese egret, hornbills and waterhens and much much more. Vending machines are weird. 3 machines right next to each other selling the same drink for $1.30, $1.20 and $1.00 respectively. You can even buy toys and water filters for literally $99??! Toys? In a wildlife reserve? Strange. Still, highly recommend this place to all who love nature and everything animals. Also, see horseshoe crabs, the oldest crabs ever!

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: definitely a very good place to just take a walk and enjoy the nature here, both fauna and flora - and to get away from the concrete jungle that is Singapore. facilities available here are surprisingly good too, and well maintained.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: This is likely Singapore's most eco-friendly park, the biodiversity bloom is so evident, and it's such a pleasure to trek through the wetlands and enjoy nature. And NPark has done an excellent job of curating an immersive experience for visitors

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: If you are into nature walks and bird watching, this is one destination you can consider! Best to drive to this place though there are also shuttle buses provided that depart from Kranji MRT station.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve - very beautiful, nature reserve in Singapore. I really love the design of the shelter very much. It looks like a bird nest, so unique and interesting.

Get to see alot of insects and animals. I'm actually afraid of insects but it was an interesting trip and I got to know alot more about the animals and insects.

Saw a couple of centipedes, caterpillars and crocodiles. There was also a crocodile name tailless cos she doesn't have a tail after a fight lol. Just take note that you will need to bring along your insect repellent and patches cos the mosquitoes at Sungei Buloh are all commandos.

The Buloh Tidal Ponds is a long track but it is reasonably shady and offers many opportunities to see some interesting creatures, like crocodile during low tide, mudskipper, spiders and  monitor lizard.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
A god tier nature attraction in Singapore, very well reserved and beautiful, it lets you get close and fully immerse into wetland environment. I went in on a Tuesday afternoon and the park was very empty and quiet (except some construction works inside), even though the area isn't that big, I still managed to walk 3.5 hours going through every trail and enjoy myself in the breathtaking nature (15:30-19:00). I was the last visitor out at 7pm. Afterwards you can walk along the bridge behind to capture the stunning Malaysia border coastline and sunset by the Kranji reservoir beach, you can even hear the loudspeakers from the mosque on the other side. It's a sight you will never forget .

About the safety, the crocodiles won't attack you if you see them, and they're the small size ones so not even close to threatening. But do be careful of a few wild dogs that live inside, the park ranger says they only bark at you and never attack, but those dogs are definitely not friendly and you would want to turn around if you see one. Also, use mosquito spray or patches.

Traffic Method: Take 925 bus at Kranji station bus stop Berth 2, get off at Kranji Reservoir Park, you'll see the entrance top right on the main road. Same when going back.

The last 925 bus back to Kranji is 8pm, so watch out for the time if you don't want to take Grab.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Great spot for birding and wildlife spotting though some people are totally innocuous of the plethora of animal and plant life in this mangrove reserve. We saw many common coastal and mangrove birds, but also a pair of Oriental pied hornbills that allowed us to watch them from 2-4 meters for 20 minutes. Also crocodiles, frogs, green whip snakes, and interesting insects. There's a colony of smal fruit bats that sleep right under on of the park bungalow areas near the museum. Testing hikers and runners were completely unaware of them until we pointed out the group of cute bats right above their heads.

But the big treat was watching a monitor lizard cannibalising an immature monitor lizard just off the path. We initially thought it was a snake, lizard, or baby crocodile but identified from the video. Not a zoo, this is real nature with all its bumps and beauty.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Arrived on a Saturday morning and was surprised to see so many people visiting the place. Learnt that there is a tour bus service from Kranji which explains the traffic. The main carpark was pretty full but we were fortunate to be able to get a lot without waiting for long. The trails are pretty easy and family/elderly friendly as most are either on proper wooden paths or well set out dirt tracks. We felt like novice hikers as most people came in fully decked out long sleeves and long pants with hats, either to avoid mosquitos or perhaps the sun. We took upon ourselves to walk about 2 of the main tracks, one to spot wildlife, mainly birds, monitor lizards, and the occasional crocodile and the other to check out the pretty instagrammable huts. We pushed ourselves to check out one more trail by driving to the other carpark, but could not find the motivation to leave the car, hence concluding our day hike experience.

All in all, the place was just how I remembered when visiting as a primary school kid on excursion. Mostly good memories.

For foodies, there isn‚Äôt much to eat in the area but a regret was not to check out Bollywood veggie which seems quite raved.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
one of the newest and best natural reservoirs in singapore. it is located at the far northwest end of the island nation, quite far from the downtown and populated residential area, no mrt nearby and few buses visiting, so overall not a famous place of interest, yet. but these may also be its advantage: far less crowded, more tranquil environment, more like a natural rainforest dominated by non-human species rather than some well developed sites.
no tickets required, walk-in is perfectly fine. also take note this is not a single park, but a reservoir consisting of several small parks, some are featured in coastal scenery, some are featured in tropical mangrove forest, some are for bird observation and some are purely for a walk in dense forests. very diverse indeed.
i believe only one or two bus reach here, and always need some walking from bus stop to the park gate, but definitely within acceptable range. after entering the park (there are toilets and information center at the main gate), you can just follow the map board inside the reservoir, or just go along whichever route you would like to explore. there are sufficient signs and map board in the reservoir so wont be worried about getting lost. the only thing is some path may be under maintenance or still construction ( mentioned early it is a rather new project)
one last thing is try to bring some insect repellent and wear long sleeves so you wont be bothered by those sometimes unknown indigenous species of flies and other creatures

Remember to bring insect repellent!

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: This is the only paradise for bird photographers in Singapore for nailing down some ultimate bird actions. This place attracts a lot of migrant birds during the seasons and we can grab a number of them form here. You would need a good telephoto zoom lens if you are really serious about photography. Because the birds would be quite far from your reach. The best time to explore this place is early morning at 7am till 9am. By then the birds will move to other resting places from their fishing zone. The entrance is completely free and not an over crowded place. As this is a place for bird watchers and photographers the place will be quite calm in the morning and everyone is so inclusive to each other. You can find people carrying huge lenses for snapping the fishing. The walk is around 2 km long around this wetland and you will find various spots where the birds occupy in the morning. There are a number of observatories and shelters around the wetland for hiding and watching the birds. You may carry some water along otherwise you might get exhausted. There are few vending machines and restrooms near the entrance so you can get water from there itself. Also as this place is near the Singapore boarder, you can get a very close view of Malaysia from here. Please check my pics here for more related views.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Spent 3 hours here doing all the walks and trails as well as searching for wildlife. Saw turtles, bats, a small crocodile, many Malaysian water monitors, fish, mudskippers, other small lizards, some birds and so many squirrels! Saw spiders too - just need to watch out and make sure you do not walk into their webs as some of them spread to the path. Many rest stops and toilet facilities. Good for some great exercise for those legs! I would come back here.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: We arrived at the Visitors Centre at 4 pm yesterday 18 April 2020 and was told that the reserve was closed due to "thundering" and all visitors must leave. It was not raining at that time.They wont even allow us to wait as they say attraction will not be reopened even though the closing time is at 7 pm. Highly disappointed as the Wetland is far from the city centre. Another couple who had arrived at the centre by taxi ($30) had to rebook a return cab without seeing the attraction. I think the center should let the visitors decide if they want to risk the rain and not act like a nanny every time. We went to the Botanic Gardens after leaving the place and even though it was "thundering " too the Gardens were not closed.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
So in love with Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve! This ecological wonder is filled with rich biodiversity and listed as ASEAN Heritage Park. Had a great time seeing its captivating and wide variety of wildlife such as saltwater crocodiles, monitor lizards, crabs, mudskippers, mud lobsters, eagles, Chinese egrets and otters.

Top Tips:
1) Go there before 8am if you want to catch a glimpse of the saltwater crocodiles. They tend to hide in the mangroves later, so it might not be too ideal to go too late.
2) If you naturally attracts mosquitoes, I highly recommend you to get an insect repellent to protect yourself from the "love" bites.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Love visiting here because you've got birds, bugs, crocs, lizards, crabs, fish and a whole forest of botany to behold!
Come early in the morning to avoid crowds. Bring a camera. Long sleeve shirts and pants are good to avoid bug bites or wear repellent.  Wear a hat. Bring water. Bring a smile and keen eyes!
Mudskipper fish at low tide are the cutest thing ever. Scarlet dragonflies are brilliant against the dark mud. Bird calls echo in the trees and across the water. Stay quiet and you may see some extra interesting birds.
The visitor center has clean restrooms. They also have a few informative displays to learn more about this unique place.
A great spot for hikes, for kids or for the elderly as the surfaces are mostly flat. Some observation area have stairs but not all.
Beautiful in any season!

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Wow! I thought this remote park reserve should be more raw like Pulau Ubin, but it actually has a lot of infrastructures! It is family friendly and the trails are in good or very good conditions.
I saw many animals: fish, snakes, lizards, birds and even crocodiles. Once section of the trail is surrounded by large spiders that can eat snakes! The body of these spiders are as long as my fingers.
Don't be worried about mosquitoes, because the spiders and dragonflies ate them all.
If you go by bus, take the 925C from Kranji MRT. Take note that this is a stop for many bird migration trips, and you'll see many bird observation hideouts. I would recommend to go during bird migration period.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: In urban Singapore, Sungei Buloh is a refreshing escape. Lush, green, studded with mangroves, its a haven for birds & birdwatchers. Even for those not in to birdwatching, this is a perfect place to enjoy nature.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Migratory Bird Trail was a great experience. If you're lucky a crocodile might even say hi to your oblivion.

Place is full of mosquitoes, so you might wanna get some repellent on standby.

Receptionist(Malay lady with slight red highlights on her hair) at Wetland Centre was so kind and helpful.Gave me a map before trailing on the Mangrove Boardwalk.Not much to see in the mangrove here, though the boardwalk gives you the 'vacation resort' vibe.

Walking on the Coastal Trail,you'll observe  onion-shaped observation hides which are picturesque enough for your IG.

Lastly, the Mid-canopy walk would perform better as a prequel to a jungle playground as its bouncy effect is a plus for playful (grown) children.

Overall,a good starting point for 'to-be-one-with-nature' hippies in rat-racing Singapore.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
It's wonderful that urban Singapore has an unspoilt corner full of wildlife and original wetlands. We spent half a day there and saw a chameleon, squirrels, monitor lizards, bats, mudskippers small and giant, spiders, insects, and lots of birds and fishes. My British guest was fully immersed in the wildlife experience and enjoyed herself very much.
Perhaps a hot drink dispenser would be a great help. No food is being sold there and as we spent a longer time than intended, we were quite hungry by the time we ended at almost 7pm, closing time. We walked out of the migratory birds route (opposite end of entrance) to the bus stop of 925# to find it non-operational on weekdays. With almost trembling legs, we walked 30min by the road to the bus stop of 925. Exhausting end to an otherwise great day. Perhaps if bicycles or buggy transport could be arranged for visitors during weekdays, that would aid tired legs from the long trudge.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: This is an excellent place for nature lovers to spend a morning or an evening. It's far from the hustle and bustle of the busy city of Singapore. In fact, it is located very close to Johor Bahru. This place is home to many birds, butterflies, some mammals, many species of fish and reptiles including the elusive crocodile. There are several viewing platforms and towers and bird hides for bird watching. In the evening, it's a delight to see numerous mudskippers climbing out of water. This place is a haven for the beautiful collared Kingfisher. Pink breasted pigeons are a common site resting on tree tops. You will see numerous egrets feeding on the banks of water masses. If you are lucky you might see redshanks, plovers etc. Fish jumping out of water in succession is an amazing treat to the eyes. Remember to take a camera with adequate telephoto reach - 600 mm minimum!

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text: Wetlands are under appreciated. Yet, they are vital to the health of an ecosystem. Examples fish nurseries, waste recycling, land stabilization i.e. protects against land erosion. Sungei Buloh has been lovingly preserved. There are well constructed walkways to enable visitors to walk into the wetlands without getting their feet wet. Also hideouts to observe the birds as they feed on the diverse marine life during low tide. Certainly recommend this as one of the must visit places in Singapore. Kudos to National Parks for making Sungei Buloh accessible.

You can spend the day here knowing you are safe here with the presences of all these photographers. Do bring you own light snacks and drinks as there are no food vendors here. However, DO keep the place clean and do NOT litter. There are bins for you to throw away you empty bottles etc...

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
You know when you're walking along and everything that moves looks like a monitor lizard, and then it turns out that they actually are monitor lizards? No? Well, you will when it you head up to Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve in northwest Singapore. I kid you not, I counted 39 monitor lizards during my walk through the mangroves over the weekend.

I didn't realise places like  Sungei Buloh existed on this island. A totally untouched, rustic spot with zero buildings on the horizon. The nature reserve is surprisingly large (I nosed around for two and a half hours and probably saw around a third) and has a nice variety of walks to get stuck into. It's only $5 to get in and has a fun visitors' centre for the little ones, and a decent-looking cafe on the way.

I started with the picturesque mangrove boardwalk and spotted a dozen mud skippers, three cockatoos, a starfish and a billion crabs (three were of the horseshoe variety). I then took 'route 1' (there are a three, of varying distances) which weaves through the forest, with the wetlands on one side and the mangroves on the other.

Hides are tucked along the path so that you can have a good stare at the hundreds of migratory birds and massive fish leaping out of the water (with splashes so loud that I initially thought a monkey had fallen into the river). I'm no twitcher, but I also spotted three collared kingfishers zipping across the freshwater ponds.

But back to the monitor lizards ‚Äì I thought I‚Äôd seen big ones at the park before, but the ones at Sungei were around three times the size. They were sunbathing on the path, swimming through the ponds, trudging through the visitors‚Äô centre and, somewhat disconcertingly, even climbing trees.

To get to the nature reserve, driving is your best option. If you don't have wheels, it's easy enough to get a cab to drop you off (I travelled from Novena and it was around $20). It's trickier to get a cab up there to take you home, so you'll probably need to get the bus from the reserve to Kranji MRT and grab the train or a taxi. The reserve's bus only goes once an hour, so it's worth asking for a look at the timetable before you head into the mangroves.

Rode past it on my long ride round 1/2 the Little Red Dot n decided to go in with my foldable bicycle on 20 Jan 2019 Sunday.

It was not buzzing with visitors. Quite a few domestic helps fr Myanmar, Indonesia n maybe Thailand in the various parts of this wetlands reserve enjoying their days off.

It is quite big as I cycled fr point to point. Being very poor in plants n other living organisms in the mangroves swamp n "forrested" areas, I was really to taking whatever I see in. Chance upon a family of monkeys by the water n surprised that these lots live in the swamp mangroves. Another eyes catching sign is: Beware of crocodiles!". Not sure I know how to respond properly n safely if one of them crawled in front of me!

As I happily rode to the Information Center, the security guard frightened me with his warning that: "I hv to take a photo of u as bicycle is NOT allowed n should be parked outside!"  I recoiled in horror as I could not afford a violation n maybe a fine in this "fine" country!! So I pleaded with him that I didn't know n this is my 1st visit! He "let me off" after consulting with his lady colleague at the counter.

Hurriedly, with my tail between my legs, I rode off!

Hope u remember to park your bike if u visit this nature reserves.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
The reserve is beautiful and surprisingly tranquil (apart from the patrolling air force jets, that is). Very glad to see that the Singaporeans had the foresight to preserve part of their wetland which represents much of Singapore's original habitat (for example, the Singapore River was once lined with mangroves). On my weekday visit it was very quiet, and long may it stay that way since the birds are vulnerable to disturbance. For example, I was able to see several kingfishers, but in most cases this was because my passing by disturbed them. The walkways are well designed to give views of mangroves, fish and other mangrove fauna as well as birds (be warned: the water monitors on the paths can easily be 5 feet long, quiet scary for some visitors). Plaques showing the main species are well done (particularly the identification flowcharts, which enabled me to identify marsh sandpipers without the benefit of binoculars). Which brings me to one suggestion: on my visit there was no way to borrow or hire binoculars. This might be feasible and could generate a little income. But even without binoculars (I had not thought birdwatching would be an option in S'pore!) Sungei Buloh was the highlight of my visit. Terima kasih!

PS I notice other visitors were bothered by mosquitoes, yet on March 13 I was not bitten once, leading me to wonder if the government had perhaps exterminated all mosquitoes from the island! But perhaps the explanation is that I was wearing beige with 4 "Moskigo" citronella pads, which I recommend strongly.

Nice and relaxing walk, would recommend it to spend few hours outside of the city!

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
review_text:
Discover the beauty and wonders of nature at Singapore‚Äôs first ASEAN Heritage Park. Uncover a world filled with rich biodiversity as you wander through the wetlands with an extensive mangrove forest of Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve.
Sungei Buloh was first opened as a Nature Park in 1993. In 2002, 130 hectares were officially gazetted as a Nature Reserve and renamed Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve to better reflect its status. In the same year, it was recognised as a site of international importance for migratory birds and awarded a certificate by Wetlands International, marking the reserve's formal entry into the East Asian Australasian Shorebird Site Network, which includes Australia's Kakadu National Park, China's Mai Po ‚Äì Inner Deep Bay and Japan's Yatsu Tidal Flats. And in 2003, Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve became Singapore's first ASEAN Heritage Park.
Since then Sungei Buloh has expanded to include 202ha of mangroves, mudflats, ponds and forests, providing an even larger sanctuary for the flora and fauna that call it home. This includes the newest extension that houses a brand new Visitor Centre and new trails for visitors to explore and enjoy. This new extension is situated along Kranji Way, and is easily accessible by public transport, bringing Sungei Buloh even closer to the public.
